1
00:00:06,380 --> 00:00:09,181
So thank you for being here.

2
00:00:09,181 --> 00:00:11,543
And so for those who don't know me, my name is Silja,

3
00:00:11,543 --> 00:00:14,164
and I have a PhD in psychology.

4
00:00:14,164 --> 00:00:15,825
And the past 10 years I've worked

5
00:00:15,825 --> 00:00:16,926
in the video game industry.

6
00:00:16,926 --> 00:00:19,187
I started at Ubisoft in France, hence the accent.

7
00:00:19,187 --> 00:00:21,769
Then I moved to Ubisoft Montreal.

8
00:00:21,769 --> 00:00:23,790
I worked at LucasArts on Star Wars games.

9
00:00:23,790 --> 00:00:28,673
And after LucasArts was bought and closed by Disney,

10
00:00:28,673 --> 00:00:30,214
I moved to Epic Games in 2013

11
00:00:30,214 --> 00:00:33,836
and worked as director of UX at the studio level.

12
00:00:34,336 --> 00:00:37,600
on many projects at Epic, including Unreal Engine,

13
00:00:37,600 --> 00:00:38,882
and of course, Fortnite.

14
00:00:38,882 --> 00:00:40,784
So this is what I'm going to talk about.

15
00:00:40,784 --> 00:00:44,769
When I arrived at Epic, there was no UX, no nothing.

16
00:00:44,769 --> 00:00:46,971
So it was like a UX team of one.

17
00:00:46,971 --> 00:00:49,875
I'm sure you're familiar with that.

18
00:00:49,875 --> 00:00:53,018
And the idea was to build it up at that time.

19
00:00:53,607 --> 00:00:55,707
So the idea of having a UX mindset,

20
00:00:55,707 --> 00:00:59,388
I love to think about UX as a mindset or a philosophy

21
00:00:59,388 --> 00:01:01,889
more than a discipline.

22
00:01:01,889 --> 00:01:03,429
Because what's important is just to try

23
00:01:03,429 --> 00:01:05,990
to place yourself in your players' shoes

24
00:01:05,990 --> 00:01:09,130
and build up all the development around it.

25
00:01:09,130 --> 00:01:12,111
And so to have a UX mindset, you have the people

26
00:01:12,111 --> 00:01:14,612
with UX in their titles, especially people

27
00:01:14,612 --> 00:01:15,632
like me coming from.

28
00:01:16,333 --> 00:01:19,096
human factors background or cognitive psychology background.

29
00:01:19,096 --> 00:01:21,779
They're here to bring UX practices.

30
00:01:21,779 --> 00:01:24,563
They're here to bring over tools and knowledge

31
00:01:24,563 --> 00:01:26,786
about the brain and all that jazz.

32
00:01:26,786 --> 00:01:29,309
And of course you have the people on the core team.

33
00:01:29,309 --> 00:01:31,812
They're here to build up the experience

34
00:01:31,812 --> 00:01:32,813
that they want to offer.

35
00:01:32,813 --> 00:01:34,575
So designers, artists, engineers.

36
00:01:34,996 --> 00:01:38,499
And you have people, so if you have a big team,

37
00:01:38,499 --> 00:01:41,442
you have people on the marketing, publishing side,

38
00:01:41,442 --> 00:01:44,525
try to define who the user is, who's your audience,

39
00:01:44,525 --> 00:01:47,607
so you can understand better what they're after,

40
00:01:47,607 --> 00:01:50,530
what they like, stuff like that.

41
00:01:50,530 --> 00:01:53,093
So by understanding your target audience,

42
00:01:53,093 --> 00:01:54,534
your users, and the experience

43
00:01:54,534 --> 00:01:56,196
that you really want to offer,

44
00:01:56,196 --> 00:01:57,957
and by having the right tools,

45
00:01:57,957 --> 00:01:59,579
this is how you have a UX mindset.

46
00:02:00,269 --> 00:02:03,011
But to get there, it's actually pretty difficult.

47
00:02:03,011 --> 00:02:05,452
You know, when in a studio, they are not

48
00:02:05,452 --> 00:02:09,494
used to these practices, you have to go step by step.

49
00:02:09,494 --> 00:02:11,375
And the first step that is important

50
00:02:11,375 --> 00:02:12,416
is to try to build trust.

51
00:02:12,416 --> 00:02:16,238
Of course, when you enter into a studio,

52
00:02:16,238 --> 00:02:21,000
they see coming a girl coming from a kind of psychology,

53
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:22,221
like a psychologist.

54
00:02:22,781 --> 00:02:25,923
So you have to make sure that they understand that you're not

55
00:02:25,923 --> 00:02:29,345
here to impede whatever they're trying to accomplish.

56
00:02:29,345 --> 00:02:30,065
You're here to help them out.

57
00:02:30,065 --> 00:02:33,588
And to do that, you need to build trust along the way.

58
00:02:33,588 --> 00:02:37,130
And also, you start by debunking some misconceptions.

59
00:02:37,130 --> 00:02:39,611
So I'm not going to talk about that too much.

60
00:02:39,611 --> 00:02:44,214
But there are some big misconceptions about UX coming

61
00:02:44,214 --> 00:02:46,115
from the game developers.

62
00:02:46,115 --> 00:02:50,257
A lot of them are afraid, which I can understand that UX will

63
00:02:50,257 --> 00:02:51,738
distort the design intentions.

64
00:02:52,118 --> 00:02:54,559
So sometimes when I talk about UX,

65
00:02:54,559 --> 00:02:56,280
I will have a game developer saying,

66
00:02:56,280 --> 00:02:57,841
what about Dark Souls?

67
00:02:57,841 --> 00:02:59,461
I'm like, what about it?

68
00:02:59,461 --> 00:03:03,043
Are you gonna, with UX and making it usable,

69
00:03:03,043 --> 00:03:06,564
you're gonna have all these games that were super hardcore,

70
00:03:06,564 --> 00:03:09,305
you're gonna change the experience of these games

71
00:03:09,305 --> 00:03:10,126
and make them all easy.

72
00:03:10,746 --> 00:03:14,850
Well, no, IQX is all about making sure that the experience you want to offer is the one

73
00:03:14,850 --> 00:03:16,591
that people experience in the end.

74
00:03:16,591 --> 00:03:22,756
So if the point of your game is to build a game that is going to be difficult to very

75
00:03:22,756 --> 00:03:27,160
specific audiences or hardcore gamers who like to suffer, we're going to absolutely

76
00:03:27,160 --> 00:03:29,141
help you accomplish your statistic goals.

77
00:03:29,141 --> 00:03:33,345
And so that's really what's important to remember, that we are here to help you out.

78
00:03:33,805 --> 00:03:41,876
So that's the one big thing you need to debunk if you're starting on a team or not used to UX and what it is.

79
00:03:41,876 --> 00:03:47,423
Try to really help them out to understand that you're here to serve them and to help them accomplish their goals.

80
00:03:48,940 --> 00:03:51,201
There's another big one is like, yeah, UX is cool,

81
00:03:51,201 --> 00:03:52,822
but we can UX it later.

82
00:03:52,822 --> 00:03:57,103
I love how people sometimes use that term as a verb,

83
00:03:57,103 --> 00:04:00,084
as if we can unfuck everything at some point later on.

84
00:04:00,084 --> 00:04:02,145
And that doesn't work as well.

85
00:04:02,145 --> 00:04:04,646
And so you have usually like the team,

86
00:04:04,646 --> 00:04:07,467
the core team's gonna iterate in a closed loop.

87
00:04:07,467 --> 00:04:08,687
And when I see that, I say,

88
00:04:08,687 --> 00:04:10,048
oh, you have some prototypes out there.

89
00:04:10,048 --> 00:04:10,628
Like, what?

90
00:04:10,628 --> 00:04:11,589
That sounds cool.

91
00:04:11,589 --> 00:04:12,789
Can we try them out?

92
00:04:12,789 --> 00:04:15,270
Can we bring players over and test it?

93
00:04:15,270 --> 00:04:16,730
And there's a lot of,

94
00:04:18,751 --> 00:04:22,756
not fear, but the developers are not super comfortable

95
00:04:22,756 --> 00:04:26,399
with that idea and they're like, no, no, no, no,

96
00:04:26,399 --> 00:04:28,562
it's ugly, it's not ready for testing, I don't want to do

97
00:04:28,562 --> 00:04:31,064
that, and that's, yeah, happened to you,

98
00:04:31,064 --> 00:04:34,528
that's something that

99
00:04:34,768 --> 00:04:38,429
it's important to understand that it's never too early to test.

100
00:04:38,429 --> 00:04:40,329
You can't test everything early,

101
00:04:40,329 --> 00:04:42,010
but there's always something that you can test,

102
00:04:42,010 --> 00:04:43,570
whether it is the menus,

103
00:04:43,570 --> 00:04:46,671
icons, the systems with dice or whatever.

104
00:04:46,671 --> 00:04:49,611
You can always prototype something to test it out.

105
00:04:49,611 --> 00:04:52,232
If you test it out when it's very early on,

106
00:04:52,232 --> 00:04:55,353
low fidelity, paper,

107
00:04:55,353 --> 00:04:58,193
before it's implemented and even better before it's added up,

108
00:04:58,193 --> 00:05:01,294
then whatever changes you need to make is actually

109
00:05:01,294 --> 00:05:04,455
faster and less costly to do than if you wait.

110
00:05:04,875 --> 00:05:07,377
too long down the line.

111
00:05:07,377 --> 00:05:09,899
So that's really important to understand.

112
00:05:09,899 --> 00:05:12,462
And here's an example of the,

113
00:05:12,462 --> 00:05:14,563
so you can tell that I am not a UX designer,

114
00:05:14,563 --> 00:05:16,905
so this is something that I put together

115
00:05:16,905 --> 00:05:21,189
to help the game designers explain

116
00:05:21,189 --> 00:05:22,710
what their vision about the game.

117
00:05:22,710 --> 00:05:23,972
Because it's also important.

118
00:05:24,192 --> 00:05:27,112
when you're on a team, it's not always about the UX

119
00:05:27,112 --> 00:05:30,033
towards the audience, your gamers, the players in the end,

120
00:05:30,033 --> 00:05:33,234
but also when you're working in a studio,

121
00:05:33,234 --> 00:05:35,355
you have to convince your bosses,

122
00:05:35,355 --> 00:05:38,115
you have to convince the executives

123
00:05:38,115 --> 00:05:39,796
that your vision is the right one,

124
00:05:39,796 --> 00:05:42,117
and this also needs good UX.

125
00:05:42,117 --> 00:05:44,857
And so this is the sort of things that,

126
00:05:44,857 --> 00:05:47,138
you know, in Fortnite you have your home base,

127
00:05:47,138 --> 00:05:49,379
this is where you grow, just helping them

128
00:05:49,379 --> 00:05:52,239
try to visualize, explain what this is gonna be about,

129
00:05:52,239 --> 00:05:52,439
and,

130
00:05:53,540 --> 00:05:57,701
When we were doing the online testing very, very early on,

131
00:05:57,701 --> 00:06:01,963
we had then a version of what the home base was,

132
00:06:01,963 --> 00:06:04,443
what was the point of the home base later on.

133
00:06:04,443 --> 00:06:07,725
But it's important to try to have a very low fidelity

134
00:06:07,725 --> 00:06:10,846
version, even if it looks a bit crappy like this one,

135
00:06:10,846 --> 00:06:14,207
just at least to make everybody on the same page

136
00:06:14,207 --> 00:06:15,127
and know where we're going.

137
00:06:17,343 --> 00:06:20,185
And so, that building that tailored relationship,

138
00:06:20,185 --> 00:06:22,426
whatever you need right now, I can help you out,

139
00:06:22,426 --> 00:06:25,088
I can help explain what you're trying to do,

140
00:06:25,088 --> 00:06:28,470
or I can help test something that you need.

141
00:06:28,470 --> 00:06:31,612
At some point during the development of Fortnite,

142
00:06:31,612 --> 00:06:35,994
the lead animator was trying to understand

143
00:06:35,994 --> 00:06:39,976
what made the husks, the little zombies,

144
00:06:39,976 --> 00:06:43,959
more difficult at times to shoot at.

145
00:06:44,659 --> 00:06:49,324
And he had like several, the team had several ideas behind it.

146
00:06:49,324 --> 00:06:53,828
Maybe the huts were moving too fast, maybe it's an animation problem.

147
00:06:53,828 --> 00:06:57,832
Maybe it is because when because these

148
00:06:57,832 --> 00:07:01,015
these enemies are the the least,

149
00:07:01,015 --> 00:07:04,558
the most frail ones, they're also the smallest ones.

150
00:07:04,558 --> 00:07:06,300
So it's.

151
00:07:06,520 --> 00:07:10,343
interesting, but because they are the level one monsters,

152
00:07:10,343 --> 00:07:13,345
they're also the ones that are harder to aim at

153
00:07:13,345 --> 00:07:15,087
from a distance because they're small.

154
00:07:15,087 --> 00:07:18,109
So maybe it's that, maybe it's something else.

155
00:07:18,109 --> 00:07:20,611
And they wanted to figure out what it was about.

156
00:07:20,611 --> 00:07:24,494
So I asked him, can you build a gym level

157
00:07:24,494 --> 00:07:26,756
so we can just spawn the zombies

158
00:07:26,756 --> 00:07:31,220
and we can ask players to shoot them as fast as possible

159
00:07:31,220 --> 00:07:32,421
and we can see what's going on

160
00:07:32,421 --> 00:07:34,502
and just reproduce a...

161
00:07:36,023 --> 00:07:39,424
the environment, typical environment in Fortnite,

162
00:07:39,424 --> 00:07:42,625
with some obstacles and the zombies will go around it.

163
00:07:42,625 --> 00:07:44,846
And so this is what we did.

164
00:07:44,846 --> 00:07:47,747
He built a gym level and we tested it.

165
00:07:47,747 --> 00:07:49,027
So it looks like this.

166
00:07:49,027 --> 00:07:50,627
The idea was we asked players,

167
00:07:50,627 --> 00:07:53,108
we pretended that there was a contest

168
00:07:53,108 --> 00:07:56,049
that the ones that were having the best score,

169
00:07:56,049 --> 00:07:57,669
we had the prize or whatever.

170
00:07:57,669 --> 00:07:59,790
So we deceived them and then it was like,

171
00:07:59,790 --> 00:08:00,370
they didn't know.

172
00:08:00,370 --> 00:08:03,531
We gave them like a chocolate bar and they were like, okay.

173
00:08:05,032 --> 00:08:08,295
But there were good sports with it.

174
00:08:08,295 --> 00:08:12,700
But the idea is to think that you're in competition

175
00:08:12,700 --> 00:08:15,022
and they had to do headshots as fast as they could

176
00:08:15,022 --> 00:08:16,744
and as many shots as they could.

177
00:08:16,744 --> 00:08:17,424
So it looks like this.

178
00:08:23,153 --> 00:08:26,976
There's no sound, but I promise you it's shooting.

179
00:08:26,976 --> 00:08:31,418
And so you see they're trying to aim at the zombies.

180
00:08:31,418 --> 00:08:31,838
Awesome.

181
00:08:31,838 --> 00:08:34,480
Doing headshots.

182
00:08:34,480 --> 00:08:36,421
And the moments when it's really harder for them

183
00:08:36,421 --> 00:08:39,803
is when zombies are going around an obstacle.

184
00:08:40,932 --> 00:08:44,354
And so that was really interesting and revealing at that moment.

185
00:08:44,354 --> 00:08:51,477
It was not, you know, there's always like several possibilities of why do we have a problem.

186
00:08:51,477 --> 00:08:56,299
But we really saw at that moment like going like the pathing code

187
00:08:56,299 --> 00:09:00,381
when a zombie had to go around something was really too sharp.

188
00:09:00,381 --> 00:09:03,863
And so this is when it was hard for players to follow that.

189
00:09:03,863 --> 00:09:07,725
So that helped us determining what was the greatest problem there.

190
00:09:08,745 --> 00:09:17,857
So really trying to be a partner, build trust, and try to find ways to test little things

191
00:09:17,857 --> 00:09:24,065
here and there and to help the team communicate what they're trying to offer was really an

192
00:09:24,065 --> 00:09:24,906
important step.

193
00:09:25,523 --> 00:09:28,886
Then the second step is to establishing quick wins.

194
00:09:28,886 --> 00:09:33,590
You want to show to the core team that a UX process, a UX

195
00:09:33,590 --> 00:09:36,953
mindset is going to help them iterate faster and have quick

196
00:09:36,953 --> 00:09:37,353
wins.

197
00:09:37,353 --> 00:09:41,877
So to do that.

198
00:09:44,160 --> 00:09:47,423
The important thing is to lay out the main limitations

199
00:09:47,423 --> 00:09:48,063
of the brain.

200
00:09:48,063 --> 00:09:49,505
And this is usually where I start,

201
00:09:49,505 --> 00:09:52,007
because I want to make sure that everybody understands that we

202
00:09:52,007 --> 00:09:53,788
have brain limitations.

203
00:09:53,788 --> 00:09:54,629
Players have them.

204
00:09:54,629 --> 00:09:55,730
We have them.

205
00:09:55,730 --> 00:09:57,572
We all in the same boat.

206
00:09:57,572 --> 00:09:59,914
And so we need to understand these limitations

207
00:09:59,914 --> 00:10:02,637
so we can correct problems when they occur.

208
00:10:03,517 --> 00:10:06,961
So this is just a very simplified, overly simplified

209
00:10:06,961 --> 00:10:10,745
diagram of what happens in your brain when you process

210
00:10:10,745 --> 00:10:12,027
information and when you learn.

211
00:10:12,027 --> 00:10:15,591
It's always starting from a perception, always starting

212
00:10:15,591 --> 00:10:18,153
from an input from your senses.

213
00:10:18,153 --> 00:10:20,496
Then you have information processing happening.

214
00:10:20,496 --> 00:10:23,279
And in the end, if you learn about something new, what's

215
00:10:23,279 --> 00:10:25,361
going to happen is it's changing something.

216
00:10:25,642 --> 00:10:27,103
in your brain physically.

217
00:10:27,103 --> 00:10:29,346
You have new synaptic connections,

218
00:10:29,346 --> 00:10:31,749
or some synapses are strengthening,

219
00:10:31,749 --> 00:10:34,252
so the synapses are connections between neurons.

220
00:10:34,252 --> 00:10:37,676
So physically, it's changing something in your brain.

221
00:10:37,676 --> 00:10:38,857
So I'm sure you know all that.

222
00:10:39,217 --> 00:10:41,218
But when you learn about something,

223
00:10:41,218 --> 00:10:43,259
it's changing your memory.

224
00:10:43,259 --> 00:10:45,801
And so during this process, there's a lot of factors,

225
00:10:45,801 --> 00:10:49,003
of course, physiological factors, biological factors.

226
00:10:49,003 --> 00:10:52,345
But the ones that I, the one I would focus on usually

227
00:10:52,345 --> 00:10:55,447
is attention, because attentional resources are scarce,

228
00:10:55,447 --> 00:10:57,528
and we know that if you don't pay attention

229
00:10:57,528 --> 00:11:00,890
to what you're doing, you're less likely to remember it.

230
00:11:00,890 --> 00:11:02,571
So attentional resources for our players

231
00:11:02,571 --> 00:11:04,012
is really important.

232
00:11:04,012 --> 00:11:06,233
And I usually also talk about emotion and motivation.

233
00:11:06,894 --> 00:11:10,056
I'll talk about that a little bit later.

234
00:11:10,056 --> 00:11:13,939
And so, and again, it's overly simplified.

235
00:11:13,939 --> 00:11:17,042
The brain is not this, it's a very complex thing

236
00:11:17,042 --> 00:11:18,583
that we barely understand.

237
00:11:18,583 --> 00:11:21,465
And it's not working in different separate buckets

238
00:11:21,465 --> 00:11:22,286
like that.

239
00:11:22,286 --> 00:11:26,549
So, it's really, you know, way more complex than that.

240
00:11:26,549 --> 00:11:29,031
But it's just to understand the main limitations

241
00:11:29,031 --> 00:11:30,492
that we're facing.

242
